<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-921-136  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 921 136.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Oct 19 1989 n1186 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Why take the machine's word for it? (overview of natural languagetranslation systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hutchins, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Natural language translators used computers in the 1940s althoughthe quality of the translated document was not good.andP;  Now, withrenewed interest in the subject, the system developer's goal hasshifted away from replacing translators and toward making themmore productive.andP;  One health organization has been improving itsSpanish-English system since 1976.andP;  The Commission of the EuropeanEconomic Community has implemented the Air Force's highly regardedRussian-English Systran mainframe.andP;  The Smart Corp tailorstranslation systems for large organizations.andP;  Japan markets manyJapanese-English interactive systems, and Siemens developed itssophisticated Metal German-English system.andP;  Powerfulmicrocomputers have also enabled multilingual program development.andO;To improve document quality, some systems use controlled language,others use a text editor and still others rely on humaninteraction.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Language TranslationNatural Language InterfacesLinguisticsForeign LanguagesResearch and Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>